[normal]Q486 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Good morning, Mr Tootell.
[normal] 
[normal]Thank you very much for coming to give evidence this morning.
[normal]              
[normal]Barry Tootell[bold]:
[normal] Good morning.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Q487 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] You were chief financial officer of the Co-op Banking Group
[normal],
[normal] from 2008 to 2011
[normal],
[normal] and then chief executive. Is that right?
[normal]Barry Tootell[bold]: Indeed.
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]Y
[normal]ou were in a key position of responsibility for the whole of the period that we are looking at?
[normal] 
[normal]Barry Tootell[bold]: Yes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q488 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Would you consider Project Verde to have been yours; that is, something that you primarily had responsibility for?
[normal]Barry Tootell[bold]: Given the significance of the Verde opportunity, it was, quite rightly, something that the group had a major hand in. The group board, together with the bank board, had concluded that it wished to pursue the opportunity that was represented by Verde.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q489 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Mr Marks tells us that this was a matter primarily for the bank and not for the group board. Who is right?
[normal]Barry Tootell[bold]: Mr Marks said it was primarily for the bank to decide whether it was able to complete the transaction. I think Mr Marks also said that he was
[normal] a driving force behind it as he
[normal] had the full support of the group board to consider the opportunity.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q490 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Where does primary responsibility lie for handling Project Verde?
[normal]Barry Tootell[bold]: Project Verde or the acquisition of a major new business is a matter reserved for the group board. As the shareholder of the banking group, the bank could not acquire a major new subsidiary or a major new undertaking without the approval of the group board. However, it would be for the bank to decide whether it was able and wished to do the transaction. So primarily the bank, but if the bank wished to pursue the transaction it would have had to have sought approval from the group board.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q491 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] We know the legal position here. We are trying to establish which individuals were driving the attempt to do this deal. Were you one of those?
[normal]Barry Tootell[bold]: I was, yes.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q492 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Were you uneasy about the deal?
[normal]Barry Tootell[bold]: I was concerned at various stages about the economic viability of the transaction, culminating in April 2013 when I recommended to my 
[normal]board
[normal] and to Peter Marks as group chief executive
[normal],
[normal] that we should not pursue the transaction because of the lack of capital strength to do so. 
[normal]A
[normal]s the group chief executive
[normal]—
[normal]given the key strategic importance of this initiative for the group
[normal]—Peter Marks was also 
[normal]the key driving force behind us exploring the opportunity.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q493 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]So y
[normal]ou were uneasy about it at various points?
[normal]Barry Tootell[bold]: Rightly so. Given the size of the transaction, it would be—
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]Q494 [bold]&#xa0; 
